Problem Statement¶

Context¶

People watch movies for various reasons. Some for entertainment as in sports and action movies, for motivation and empowerment as in inspirational movies, others for the purposes of learning new things as in documentaries. The movie industry is a lucarative industry and has been growing steadily over the years. Internet Movie Database (IMDb) is an online database for movies, home videos, television series, etc. Users can post their ratings of movies on the site. People use the site to choose theirs movies of interest and decide on which movies are worth watching. As of March 2022, the database contained some 10.1 million titles (including television episodes) and 11.5 million person records. Additionally, the site had 83 million registered users.

Objective¶

Carry out analysis on the imdb movies dataset to determine the following:

  1. Factors that affects movie revenue
  2. The popular genres of movies for each year
  3. the growth of movie industry based on movies release by year

Dataset Description¶

The dataset has the following information¶
id: id of the file¶
imdd_id : the imdb unique reference for the movie¶
popularity : popularity ratings for the movie¶
budget : the bugdet of the movie¶
revenue : revenue generated from the movie sales¶
original_title : title of the movie¶
cast : popular actors in the movie¶
homepage : Website for the movie¶
director : Name of the directors¶
tagline : movie tagline¶
overview : a brief description of the movie¶
runtime : duration of the moview in minutes¶
genres : the genres the movie falls into¶
production_company : Companies that produced the movie¶
release_date : date on which the movie was released¶
vote_count : total no of votes on the movie at the site¶
vote_average : an average of the vote counts¶
release_year : the year the movie was released¶
budget_adj : adjusted budget to cater for inflation¶
revenue_adj : adjusted revenue to cater for inflation¶

# indivual Genres
# Which genre features more in the genre list
genre_data = dict()
exceptions = []
for genre in df.genres:
    try:
        for g in genre.split('|'):
            #print(g)
            if g in genre_data:
                genre_data[g] +=1
            else:
                genre_data[g] = 1
    except:
        exceptions.append(genre)

Explore Factors that affect revenue¶

In [17]:
#separate data into categorical and numerical columns
numerical_cols = [df.columns[i] for i in range(len(df.columns)) if df.dtypes[i] !='object']
categorical_cols = [df.columns[i] for i in range(len(df.columns)) if df.dtypes[i] =='object']

Separating data into categorical and numerical sets informs the kind of analysis to perform on each variable. We can look at boxplots for outliers and scatter plots for linear relationships amongst the numerical variables

In [18]:
# define a scatter plot function 
def display_scatterplot(x, y, xlabel, ylabel, title):
    '''
    Draw a scatter plot with the following input variables x, y. 
    This plot shows the relationship between two numerical variables
    
    xlabel and ylabel are the labels for the x and y values respectively
    title : the title of the plot
    
    '''
    
    plt.scatter(x, y)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()
In [19]:
# Anaylse runtime with the other categorical values
for i in range(len(numerical_cols)):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,4))
    y = df.runtime
    x = df[numerical_cols[i]]
    sp_title = f'Scatter Plot between Runtime and {numerical_cols[i]} '
    print('\n')
    display_scatterplot(x,y, ylabel='Runtime', xlabel=str(numerical_cols[i]), title=sp_title)
    plt.show()

Observation : The runtime is not dependent on the release year. Movies release in the 1960s have similar runtimes with those release post 2010s.

In [20]:
#Analyse popularity along with other numerical columns
for i in range(len(numerical_cols)):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,4))
    y = df.popularity
    x = df[numerical_cols[i]]
    sp_title = f' popularity and {numerical_cols[i]} '
    print('\n')
    display_scatterplot(x,y, ylabel='popularity', xlabel=str(numerical_cols[i]), title=sp_title)
    plt.show()

Observation : The more popular a movie is the higher the vote count. Similarly, more popular movies record more revenue. Movies with less runtime typically below 200 minutes are more popular than those above 200. We can deduce that people loose interest in longer running movies.

In [21]:
# Compare Revenue with the other numerical values
for i in range(len(numerical_cols)):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,4))
    y = df.revenue
    x = df[numerical_cols[i]]
    sp_title = f' revenue and {numerical_cols[i]} '
    print('\n')
    display_scatterplot(x,y, ylabel='revenue', xlabel=str(numerical_cols[i]), title=sp_title)
    plt.show()

Observation: As budget rise, the revenue also rises. This mean that highly budgeted movies are more likely to generate high revenues. We saw in the previous analysis that movies with less runtime are more popular, here we see that movies with less runtime also generate high revenue. This implies that runtime and popularity have an effect on revenue.

Conclusion¶

The exploratory data analysis showed what really impact revenue for movies. It also show that the movie industry is growing and as more and more movies are being released each year. As people's interest in a movie grows, it's popularity also grows. The vote count can be used to determine the popularity of the movie. As a movie becomes popular, it turns to generate more revenue. Although correlation does not always imply causation, the data available seems to strongly suggest that popularity, budget and vote count have a strong effect on the revenue.

The columns dropped had no effect on the analysis. The genres were grouped together, this made it challenging to clearly show the effect the genres have on the popularity of the movie.
